    "cosy_axis_max": 40,
    "selector": "Frontal Lobectomy Surgery",
    "selector_info": "Selecting \"Yes\" indicates that the patient underwent a frontal lobectomy as part of the surgical treatment for tumor-related epilepsy. According to the study, seizure freedom was achieved in 81.1% of patients postoperatively (Engel I classification) at follow-up periods of six months or more. The study highlights that a gross total resection (GTR) significantly improves seizure outcomes, with an odds ratio of 8.77 for achieving seizure freedom. Awake surgery was also identified as a predictive factor for favorable outcomes in this context. The analysis included 127 patients with low-grade, intra-axial, glial, or glioneuronal tumors located in the frontal lobe. Tumor types included oligodendrogliomas (50.4%), astrocytomas, gangliogliomas, and dysembryoplastic neuroepithelial tumors (DNETs).",
